{"title_page": "Sy Rogers", "text_new": "{{short description|American Christian pastor}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Sy Rogers\n| image         = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = \n| birth_place   = United States\n| death_date    = 19 April 2020 (age 63)\n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = [[Americans|American]]\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = [[Pastor]], [[activism|activist]]\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n}}\n'''Sy Rogers''' (died April 20, 2020) was an American Christian pastor who was part of the [[ex-gay movement]]. In the late 1980s, Rogers was a President of [[Exodus International]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/national/gods-cure-for-gays-lost-in-sin/2008/03/18/1205602385236.html |title=God's cure for gays lost in sin|date=March 19, 2008|website=smh.com.au|accessdate=11 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://nacla.org/news/2015/03/30/change-possible-sexual-conversions-and-imperial-aspirations-americas|title=Change is Possible: Sexual Conversions and Imperial Aspirations in the Americas|website=NACLA|accessdate=11 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Venn-Brown |first1=Anthony |title=Sy Rogers \u2013 is his message homosexual re-orientation? |url=http://www.abbi.org.au/2017/03/sy-rogers-2-2/ |website=abbi.org |date=March 6, 2017}}</ref> and became one of the earliest noted personalities associated with the ex-gay movement during the early 1980s.  He wrote a life-story testimony entitled \"The Man in the Mirror,\" which was published in pamphlet form by [[Last Days Ministries]].<ref name=\"WhiteProfile\">{{cite news |last1=White |first1=Russ |title=If I Can Change, You Can, Former Transsexual Tells Gays |url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/1987-08-01/news/0180420138_1_homosexuality-2-corinthians-rogers |accessdate=4 March 2019 |publisher=Orlando Sentinel |date=1 August 1987}}</ref><ref name=\"KennedyStraight\"/>\n\n== Life and career ==\nAs a young man, Rogers was involved in the gay community and had physical relationships with men. He later identified as transsexual, living as a woman for a year and a half and beginning the process of arranging to have sex-change surgery.<ref name=\"MaraghyDenial\">{{cite news |last1=Maraghy |first1=Mary |title=Ministries reaching sexually 'broken' But gay pastor says they teach people to live in denial |publisher=[[Florida Times Union]] |date=24 November 2001|id={{ProQuest|414208878}} }}</ref><ref name=CharismaChild/><ref>{{cite web |last1=Rogers |first1=Sy |title=The Man In The Mirror |url=https://www.exodusglobalalliance.org/themaninthemirrorp338.php |website=www.exodusglobalalliance.org|quote=Though I did not get around to ever having the surgery, I was on hormone therapy and lived as a woman for about a year and a half.}}</ref> He credited his conversion to Christianity for igniting personal growth and a new-found security in gender identity which enabled a shift in his sexuality to heterosexual.<ref name=\"KennedyStraight\"/>  He stated in his personal story, \"My goal was not to be straight--it was God\". He married a woman he met in a Bible-study group, began to identify as heterosexual,<ref name=CharismaChild>{{cite web|url=http://www.charismanews.com/opinion/watchman-on-the-wall/40436-transgender-agenda-finds-father-knows-best-style-poster-child|title=Transgender Agenda Finds 'Father Knows Best'- Style Poster Child|work=Charismanews.com|accessdate=28 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.charismanews.com/opinion/watchman-on-the-wall/40459-did-pat-robertson-really-endorse-the-transgender-movement|title=Did Pat Robertson Really Endorse The Transgender Movement?|work=charismanews.com|accessdate=28 February 2019}}</ref> and they had a family together.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=-oW2afN9FWQC&pg=PA230&dq=%22balanced+ministry+to+homosexuals%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjvrZjJyt_gAhUJ1oMKHetlBuMQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=%22balanced%20ministry%20to%20homosexuals%22&f=false The Gay Gospel?] By Joe Dallas</ref><ref name=\"KennedyStraight\"/><ref name=\"MaraghyDenial\"/> \n\nIn 1988, Rogers then 30, a married father, living in Florida, self-describing as a former homosexual and former transsexual,  told a reporter for the Chicago Sun-Times that the ex-gay movement was not anti-gay, \"If you want to stay gay, that's your business,... But the bottom line is, you have a choice to overcome it. You can change.\"<ref name=\"KennedyStraight\">{{cite news |last1=Kennedy |first1=Dana |title=Helping gays go straight |publisher=Chicago Sun-Times |date=14 January 1988|id={{ProQuest|257259079}} }}</ref> \"The goal is God--not going straight. Straight people don't go to Heaven, redeemed people do.\" \n\nDuring Rogers' involvement in the mid to late 1980s, Exodus International had offices on five continents and declared that \"all homosexual relationships are sinful.\"<ref name=\"RussellHomosexuals\">{{cite news |last1=Russell |first1=Candice |title=GOING STRAIGHT DOCUMENTARY FOCUSES ON EFFORTS TO 'CURE' HOMOSEXUALS |publisher=Sun Sentinel |date=14 June 1994|id={{ProQuest|388682062}} }}</ref> In conducting a speaking tour in 2008 Rogers\u2019 message included, \"Homosexuality is out of tune with religion; it is not what God planned for human sexuality.\" <ref name=\"MaraghyDenial\" /><ref name=\"PollardInvestigation\">{{cite news |last1=Pollard |first1=Ruth |title=God's cure for gays lost in sin: FACING THEIR DEMONS - A HERALD INVESTIGATION |publisher=Sydney Morning Herald |date=19 March 2008|id={{ProQuest|364377547}} }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Bruce, Clara.|url=https://hope1032.com.au/stories/faith/christian-living/2017/sy-rogers-message-grace-sexual-brokenness-colour-conference/|title=Sy Rogers' Message of Grace for Sexual Brokenness, at Colour Conference |website=[[Hope 103.2]] |date=2017-03-01 |accessdate=2019-02-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/southland-times/news/10289301/Youths-flock-to-Queenstown-for-conference|title=Youths flock to Queenstown for conference |website=Southland Times |date=2014-07-21 |accessdate=2019-03-04}}</ref><ref name=\"PollardInvestigation\" /> Writing in [[The Gay & Lesbian Review Worldwide]], gay rights advocate [[Wayne Besen]] argued that during the AIDS epidemic \"some men were literally scared straight - or at least into making the futile attempt,\" bringing a degree of momentary success to Exodus International.<ref name=\"BesenMovement\">{{cite journal |last1=Besen |first1=Wayne |title=The Politics of the Ex-Gay Movement |journal=The Gay & Lesbian Review Worldwide |date=July 2007 |volume=14 |issue=4 |id={{ProQuest|198678084}} }}</ref> In 2016, ''[[The Daily Beast]]'' reported that Rogers's ministry had moved away from the ex-gay message many years earlier.<ref name=\"TDB\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2016/01/17/sex-abuse-gay-conversion-therapy-the-dark-past-of-justin-bieber-s-megachurch-hillsong.html|title=Sex Abuse & Gay Conversion Therapy: The Dark Past of Justin Bieber's Megachurch Hillsong|author=Zadrozny, Brandy|date=January 16, 2016|work=[[The Daily Beast]]}}</ref>\n\nRogers is portrayed in the 1993 documentary ''[[One Nation Under God (1993 film)|One Nation Under God]]''.<ref name=\"RussellHomosexuals\"/><ref name=\"BesenMovement\"/><ref name=\"SinclairStudents\">{{cite news |last1=Sinclair |first1=Harriet |title=U.S.'s Richest Boarding School Admits It Showed Anti-Gay Videos To Students |url=https://www.newsweek.com/countrys-richest-boarding-school-admits-it-showed-anti-gay-videos-students-634528 |accessdate=4 March 2019 |publisher=Newsweek |date=10 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nRogers and his wife Karen married in 1982 and had children and grandchildren.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://now.hillsongchannel.com/colour-conference-the-green-room/videos/hillsongchannel-colour-conference-the-green-room-s3-e7-mezzanine|title=Sy & Karen Rogers|website=Hillsong Channel NOW|language=en|access-date=2019-04-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://syrogers.com/speaking/sy-bio/|title=Sy Bio {{!}} Sy Rogers|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-03}}</ref> From 2012, he was a Teaching Pastor with the multi-campus LIFE Church & College in Auckland, New Zealand.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rhema.co.nz/shows-djs/interviews/item/178-sy-rodgers-chats-with-andrew|title=Sy Rogers chats with Andrew|last=Ashcroft|first=Nerida|website=www.rhema.co.nz|language=en-gb|access-date=2019-04-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thelifechurch.com/posts/guest-speaker-sy-rogers|title=Guest Speaker: Sy Rogers|website=thelifechurch.com|access-date=2019-04-03}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 April 2020, Life Church NZ posted to Instagram that Rogers had died.<ref name=\"Life Church NZ on Instagram\">https://www.instagram.com/p/B_Mon-hgoJv/</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{imdb name|nm4937197}}\n* {{official|http://www.syrogers.com}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rogers, Sy}}\n[[Category:American Christian clergy]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:American activists]]\n[[Category:Ex-gay movement]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from the United States]]\n[[Category:People who detransitioned]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]yo say he\u2019s living? me not thinks so\n{{authority control}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American Christian pastor}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Sy Rogers\n| image         = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = \n| birth_place   = United States\n| death_date    = 19 April 2020 (age 63)\n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = [[Americans|American]]\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = [[Pastor]], [[activism|activist]]\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n}}\n'''Sy Rogers''' (died April 20, 2020) was an American Christian pastor who was part of the [[ex-gay movement]]. In the late 1980s, Rogers was a President of [[Exodus International]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/national/gods-cure-for-gays-lost-in-sin/2008/03/18/1205602385236.html |title=God's cure for gays lost in sin|date=March 19, 2008|website=smh.com.au|accessdate=11 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://nacla.org/news/2015/03/30/change-possible-sexual-conversions-and-imperial-aspirations-americas|title=Change is Possible: Sexual Conversions and Imperial Aspirations in the Americas|website=NACLA|accessdate=11 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Venn-Brown |first1=Anthony |title=Sy Rogers \u2013 is his message homosexual re-orientation? |url=http://www.abbi.org.au/2017/03/sy-rogers-2-2/ |website=abbi.org |date=March 6, 2017}}</ref> and became one of the earliest noted personalities associated with the ex-gay movement during the early 1980s.  He wrote a life-story testimony entitled \"The Man in the Mirror,\" which was published in pamphlet form by [[Last Days Ministries]].<ref name=\"WhiteProfile\">{{cite news |last1=White |first1=Russ |title=If I Can Change, You Can, Former Transsexual Tells Gays |url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/1987-08-01/news/0180420138_1_homosexuality-2-corinthians-rogers |accessdate=4 March 2019 |publisher=Orlando Sentinel |date=1 August 1987}}</ref><ref name=\"KennedyStraight\"/>\n\n== Life and career ==\nAs a young man, Rogers was involved in the gay community and had physical relationships with men. He later identified as transsexual, living as a woman for a year and a half and beginning the process of arranging to have sex-change surgery.<ref name=\"MaraghyDenial\">{{cite news |last1=Maraghy |first1=Mary |title=Ministries reaching sexually 'broken' But gay pastor says they teach people to live in denial |publisher=[[Florida Times Union]] |date=24 November 2001|id={{ProQuest|414208878}} }}</ref><ref name=CharismaChild/><ref>{{cite web |last1=Rogers |first1=Sy |title=The Man In The Mirror |url=https://www.exodusglobalalliance.org/themaninthemirrorp338.php |website=www.exodusglobalalliance.org|quote=Though I did not get around to ever having the surgery, I was on hormone therapy and lived as a woman for about a year and a half.}}</ref> He credited his conversion to Christianity for igniting personal growth and a new-found security in gender identity which enabled a shift in his sexuality to heterosexual.<ref name=\"KennedyStraight\"/>  He stated in his personal story, \"My goal was not to be straight--it was God\". He married a woman he met in a Bible-study group, began to identify as heterosexual,<ref name=CharismaChild>{{cite web|url=http://www.charismanews.com/opinion/watchman-on-the-wall/40436-transgender-agenda-finds-father-knows-best-style-poster-child|title=Transgender Agenda Finds 'Father Knows Best'- Style Poster Child|work=Charismanews.com|accessdate=28 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.charismanews.com/opinion/watchman-on-the-wall/40459-did-pat-robertson-really-endorse-the-transgender-movement|title=Did Pat Robertson Really Endorse The Transgender Movement?|work=charismanews.com|accessdate=28 February 2019}}</ref> and they had a family together.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=-oW2afN9FWQC&pg=PA230&dq=%22balanced+ministry+to+homosexuals%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjvrZjJyt_gAhUJ1oMKHetlBuMQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=%22balanced%20ministry%20to%20homosexuals%22&f=false The Gay Gospel?] By Joe Dallas</ref><ref name=\"KennedyStraight\"/><ref name=\"MaraghyDenial\"/> \n\nIn 1988, Rogers then 30, a married father, living in Florida, self-describing as a former homosexual and former transsexual,  told a reporter for the Chicago Sun-Times that the ex-gay movement was not anti-gay, \"If you want to stay gay, that's your business,... But the bottom line is, you have a choice to overcome it. You can change.\"<ref name=\"KennedyStraight\">{{cite news |last1=Kennedy |first1=Dana |title=Helping gays go straight |publisher=Chicago Sun-Times |date=14 January 1988|id={{ProQuest|257259079}} }}</ref> \"The goal is God--not going straight. Straight people don't go to Heaven, redeemed people do.\" \n\nDuring Rogers' involvement in the mid to late 1980s, Exodus International had offices on five continents and declared that \"all homosexual relationships are sinful.\"<ref name=\"RussellHomosexuals\">{{cite news |last1=Russell |first1=Candice |title=GOING STRAIGHT DOCUMENTARY FOCUSES ON EFFORTS TO 'CURE' HOMOSEXUALS |publisher=Sun Sentinel |date=14 June 1994|id={{ProQuest|388682062}} }}</ref> In conducting a speaking tour in 2008 Rogers\u2019 message included, \"Homosexuality is out of tune with religion; it is not what God planned for human sexuality.\" <ref name=\"MaraghyDenial\" /><ref name=\"PollardInvestigation\">{{cite news |last1=Pollard |first1=Ruth |title=God's cure for gays lost in sin: FACING THEIR DEMONS - A HERALD INVESTIGATION |publisher=Sydney Morning Herald |date=19 March 2008|id={{ProQuest|364377547}} }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Bruce, Clara.|url=https://hope1032.com.au/stories/faith/christian-living/2017/sy-rogers-message-grace-sexual-brokenness-colour-conference/|title=Sy Rogers' Message of Grace for Sexual Brokenness, at Colour Conference |website=[[Hope 103.2]] |date=2017-03-01 |accessdate=2019-02-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/southland-times/news/10289301/Youths-flock-to-Queenstown-for-conference|title=Youths flock to Queenstown for conference |website=Southland Times |date=2014-07-21 |accessdate=2019-03-04}}</ref><ref name=\"PollardInvestigation\" /> Writing in [[The Gay & Lesbian Review Worldwide]], gay rights advocate [[Wayne Besen]] argued that during the AIDS epidemic \"some men were literally scared straight - or at least into making the futile attempt,\" bringing a degree of momentary success to Exodus International.<ref name=\"BesenMovement\">{{cite journal |last1=Besen |first1=Wayne |title=The Politics of the Ex-Gay Movement |journal=The Gay & Lesbian Review Worldwide |date=July 2007 |volume=14 |issue=4 |id={{ProQuest|198678084}} }}</ref> In 2016, ''[[The Daily Beast]]'' reported that Rogers's ministry had moved away from the ex-gay message many years earlier.<ref name=\"TDB\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2016/01/17/sex-abuse-gay-conversion-therapy-the-dark-past-of-justin-bieber-s-megachurch-hillsong.html|title=Sex Abuse & Gay Conversion Therapy: The Dark Past of Justin Bieber's Megachurch Hillsong|author=Zadrozny, Brandy|date=January 16, 2016|work=[[The Daily Beast]]}}</ref>\n\nRogers is portrayed in the 1993 documentary ''[[One Nation Under God (1993 film)|One Nation Under God]]''.<ref name=\"RussellHomosexuals\"/><ref name=\"BesenMovement\"/><ref name=\"SinclairStudents\">{{cite news |last1=Sinclair |first1=Harriet |title=U.S.'s Richest Boarding School Admits It Showed Anti-Gay Videos To Students |url=https://www.newsweek.com/countrys-richest-boarding-school-admits-it-showed-anti-gay-videos-students-634528 |accessdate=4 March 2019 |publisher=Newsweek |date=10 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nRogers and his wife Karen married in 1982 and had children and grandchildren.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://now.hillsongchannel.com/colour-conference-the-green-room/videos/hillsongchannel-colour-conference-the-green-room-s3-e7-mezzanine|title=Sy & Karen Rogers|website=Hillsong Channel NOW|language=en|access-date=2019-04-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://syrogers.com/speaking/sy-bio/|title=Sy Bio {{!}} Sy Rogers|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-03}}</ref> From 2012, he was a Teaching Pastor with the multi-campus LIFE Church & College in Auckland, New Zealand.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rhema.co.nz/shows-djs/interviews/item/178-sy-rodgers-chats-with-andrew|title=Sy Rogers chats with Andrew|last=Ashcroft|first=Nerida|website=www.rhema.co.nz|language=en-gb|access-date=2019-04-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thelifechurch.com/posts/guest-speaker-sy-rogers|title=Guest Speaker: Sy Rogers|website=thelifechurch.com|access-date=2019-04-03}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 April 2020, Life Church NZ posted to Instagram that Rogers had died.<ref name=\"Life Church NZ on Instagram\">https://www.instagram.com/p/B_Mon-hgoJv/</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{imdb name|nm4937197}}\n* {{official|http://www.syrogers.com}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rogers, Sy}}\n[[Category:American Christian clergy]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:American activists]]\n[[Category:Ex-gay movement]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from the United States]]\n[[Category:People who detransitioned]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n{{authority control}}\n", "name_user": "5.90.171.77", "label": "vandal", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eExternal links)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sy_Rogers"}
{"title_page": "Randy Oda", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Randy Oda\n| image              = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = Randall Keith Oda\n| birth_date         = 1953\n| birth_place        = El Cerrito, California\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| occupation         = Guitarist, composer\n}}\n\n'''Randy Oda''' (born 1953) is a composer and musician who performed with  [[Tom Fogerty]] and the band [[Ruby (Ruby album)|Ruby]], producing the albums ''[[Ruby (Ruby album)|Ruby]]'', ''[[Rock & Roll Madness]],'' ''[[Precious Gems]]'', and [[Sidekicks (album)|Sidekicks]]. He composed [[Eddie Money]]'s 1982 hit song, \"[[Think I'm in Love (Eddie Money song)|Think I'm in Love]]\", which [[Arnold Schwarzenegger]] also used on an exercise video. His \"BART\" instrumental was used by BBC School Music during intervals. His latest band is 'OPO.\n\n== Early life and education ==\nRandall Keith Oda was born in 1953 in [[Alameda County, California]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ancestry.com/cs/offers/join?sub=2550866976735232&dbid=5247&url=https%3a%2f%2fsearch.ancestry.com%2fcgi-bin%2fsse.dll%3findiv%3d1%26dbid%3d5247%26h%3d5348458%26usePUB%3dtrue%26_phsrc%3dSoG4%26_phstart%3dsuccessSource%26requr%3d2550866976735232%26ur%3d0&gsfn=&gsln=&h=5348458|title=California Birth Index, 1905-1995|last=Oda|first=Randall Keith|date=1983|website=www.ancestry.com|url-access=subscription|url-status=live|access-date=2020-01-15|quote=Name: Randall Keith Oda - Birth: 1953 - Gender: Male - Mother's Maiden Name: Harada - Birth County: Alameda}}</ref> He attended [[John F. Kennedy High School (Richmond, California)|Kennedy High School]] in [[Richmond, California]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/42204490/tom-fogerty-invites-you-to-dance/|title=Tom Fogerty Invites You to Dance|date=1976-10-23|work=The Berkeley Gazette|access-date=2020-04-14|pages=20}}</ref> Oda married Jean Nugent in 1985.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ancestry.com/cs/offers/join?sub=2550866976735232&dbid=1144&url=https%3a%2f%2fsearch.ancestry.com%2fcgi-bin%2fsse.dll%3fdbid%3d1144%26h%3d1645299%26indiv%3dtry%26o_vc%3dRecord%3aOtherRecord%26rhSource%3d5247%26requr%3d2550866976735232%26ur%3d0&gsfn=&gsln=&h=1645299|title=California Marriage Index|website=www.ancestry.com|url-access=subscription|url-status=live|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nBeginning in late 1971, Randy Oda, his brother Kevin Oda, Art Pantoja, and Kyle Schneider formed the band \"Oda\", which producing two albums on the Loud Phonograph Albums label.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/42203935/oda_likes_its_records_loud/|title=Oda  Likes Its Records Loud|date=1973-03-17|access-date=2020-01-13|pages=24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/artist/2069706-Oda-4|title=Oda (4)|website=Discogs|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> A local [[San Francisco Bay Area|Bay Area]] band, they played gigs in Berkely.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/42204665/keystone_date/|title=Keystone Date|date=1980-08-29|access-date=2020-01-13|pages=19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/42203521/oda_joy_of_it/|title=Oda Joy of It|date=1983-01-14|work=The Berkeley Gazette|access-date=2020-01-13|pages=19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/43651601/rocker_randy_oda_plays_at_keystone/|title=Rocker Randy Oda plays at Keystone Wednesday|date=1981-12-25|work=The Berkeley Gazette|access-date=2020-02-05|pages=48}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/43651584/oda_headlines_keystone_friday/|title=Oda headlines Keystone Friday|date=1983-02-03|work=The Berkeley Gazette|access-date=2020-02-05|pages=14}}</ref> They played a reunion benefit at [[Concord, California|Concord]] in 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eastbaytimes.com/2015/01/21/chris-treadway-world-series-trophies-playland-reading-benefit-and-garage-band-reunion/|title=Chris Treadway: World Series trophies, Playland reading benefit and garage band reunion|date=2015-01-21|website=East Bay Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-12}}</ref>\n\nIn the early 1970's, Oda joined Tom Fogerty in the band Ruby, with Oda on guitar, Anthony Davis on bass, and [[Bobby Cochran]] on drums. Reviewer Phillip Elwood wrote, \"...when Randy Oda, nominally the band's solo guitar, gets into an extended theme the band backs him with all the flair of a seasoned jazz-blues-rock orchestra.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/42204168/ruby_is_a_futuristic_gem_of_electric/|title=Ruby Is a Futuristic Gem of Electric Rock|date=1976-01-09|work=The San Francisco Examiner|access-date=2020-01-13|pages=25}}</ref>\n\nIn a 1978 review of Ruby, Greg Beese said Oda was \"a session musician prior to joining Ruby, playing on television and radio commercials, including those for [[McDonald's|McDonalds]] restaurants. His sounds transcends the [[Big Mac]], though, as he is a sensitive and hot guitarist. His instrumental composition \"BART\" (after [[Bay Area Rapid Transit]]) immediately picked up the show and shook up the crowd Friday night. Oda's instrumental compositions are not unlike [[Jeff Beck]] or [[Pablo Cruise]] in the way they build up to a whining crescendo.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/42202906/ruby_pleasant_surprise_for_civic/|title=Ruby Pleasant Surprise for Civic|date=1978-04-02|work=Santa Cruz Sentinel|access-date=2020-01-13|pages=17}}</ref> Oda's \"BART\" instrumental was used by the [[BBC]] in school intervals during the 1970s and 1980s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://viralhub.video/video/vfC8M-mTBMM/bbc-schools-music-bart-by-ruby-on-pages-from-ceefax-18th-november-2005|title=BBC Schools Music Bart By Ruby On Pages From Ceefax 18th November 2005|website=viralhub.video|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\nRuby released two studio albums, ''[[Ruby (Ruby album)|Ruby]]'' in 1976<ref>{{Citation|title=Ruby - Ruby {{!}} Songs, Reviews, Credits {{!}} AllMusic|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/ruby-mw0000846581|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> and ''[[Rock & Roll Madness]]'' in 1978,<ref>{{Citation|title=Rock'n'Roll Madness - Ruby {{!}} Songs, Reviews, Credits {{!}} AllMusic|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/rocknroll-madness-mw0000848018|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> and then disbanded. They released ''[[Precious Gems]]'', a compliation album, in 1984. Oda and Fogerty's ''[[Sidekicks (album)|Sidekicks]] was'' released in 1992 after Fogerty died,<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/43648477/rockin_island_style/|title=Rockin' island style|date=2015-06-18|work=Rapid City Journal|access-date=2020-02-05|pages=32}}</ref> with Oda's credits on the album listed as \"Arranger, Composer, Guitar (Acoustic), Guitar (Electric), Keyboards, Primary Artist, Producer\".<ref>{{Citation|title=Sidekicks - Tom Fogerty {{!}} Credits {{!}} AllMusic|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/sidekicks-mw0000094869/credits|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> \n\nOda composed Eddie Money's 1982 single, \"[[Think I'm in Love (Eddie Money song)|Think I'm in Love]]\", which reached #1 on the ''Billboard'' [[Hot Mainstream Rock Tracks|Top Tracks]] chart.<ref>[[Joel Whitburn|Whitburn, Joel]] (2004). ''The Billboard Book of Top 40 Hits'', 8th Edition (Billboard Publications), page 433.</ref> It appeared on Money's 1983 album, ''[[No Control (Eddie Money album)|No Control]]'',<ref>{{Citation|title=No Control - Eddie Money {{!}} Songs, Reviews, Credits {{!}} AllMusic|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/no-control-mw0000191044|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> as well as [[Arnold Schwarzenegger's Total Body Workout|''Arnold Schwarzenegger's Total Body Workout'']] video,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/arnold-schwarzeneggers-total-body-workout-mw0000324378|title=Arnold Schwarzenegger's Total Body Workout - Arnold Schwarzenegger {{!}} Songs, Reviews, Credits|website=AllMusic|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> and multiple compilation albums.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/randy-oda-mn0000397161/credits|title=Randy Oda {{!}} Credits|website=AllMusic|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\nOda joined his brother Kevin Oda on drums and Michael Politeau (bass) in the band 'OPO, an acronym for its members (Oda, Politeau, Oda), which also means \"to lay a foundation\" in Hawaiian.<ref name=\":0\" /> 'OPO produced the album ''Getaway'' in 2011.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/getaway-mw0002200311|title=Getaway - 'Opo {{!}} Songs, Reviews, Credits|website=AllMusic|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/getaway-mw0002200311/releases|title=Getaway - 'Opo Releases|website=AllMusic|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [http://oposongs.com/bio.html 'OPO band website]\n*{{YouTube|id=59pbyJ4dVrU|title=Think I'm in Love}} (video, 2:37 minute)\n* {{YouTube|title=Oda - I Got a Mind to Give Up Living|id=wiQjBcViiYI}} (audio, 6:25 minutes)\n* {{YouTube|id=vfC8M-mTBMM|title=BART on BBC}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Oda, Randy}}\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American guitarists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American musicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American guitarists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American musicians]]\n[[Category:American male guitarists]]\n[[Category:American rock guitarists]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from California]]\n[[Category:People from Contra Costa County, California]]\n[[Category:Rhythm guitarists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Randy Oda\n| image              = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = Randall Keith Oda\n| birth_date         = 1953\n| birth_place        = El Cerrito, California\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| occupation         = Guitarist, composer\n}}\n\n'''Randy Oda''' (born 1953) is a composer and musician who performed with  [[Tom Fogerty]] and the band [[Ruby (Ruby album)|Ruby]], producing the albums ''[[Ruby (Ruby album)|Ruby]]'', ''[[Rock & Roll Madness]],'' ''[[Precious Gems]]'', and [[Sidekicks (album)|Sidekicks]]. He composed [[Eddie Money]]'s 1982 hit song, \"[[Think I'm in Love (Eddie Money song)|Think I'm in Love]]\", which [[Arnold Schwarzenegger]] also used on an exercise video. His \"BART\" instrumental was used by BBC School Music during intervals. His latest band is 'OPO.\n\n== Early life and education ==\nRandall Keith Oda was born in 1953 in [[Alameda County, California]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ancestry.com/cs/offers/join?sub=2550866976735232&dbid=5247&url=https%3a%2f%2fsearch.ancestry.com%2fcgi-bin%2fsse.dll%3findiv%3d1%26dbid%3d5247%26h%3d5348458%26usePUB%3dtrue%26_phsrc%3dSoG4%26_phstart%3dsuccessSource%26requr%3d2550866976735232%26ur%3d0&gsfn=&gsln=&h=5348458|title=California Birth Index, 1905-1995|last=Oda|first=Randall Keith|date=1983|website=www.ancestry.com|url-access=subscription|url-status=live|access-date=2020-01-15|quote=Name: Randall Keith Oda - Birth: 1953 - Gender: Male - Mother's Maiden Name: Harada - Birth County: Alameda}}</ref> He attended [[John F. Kennedy High School (Richmond, California)|Kennedy High School]] in [[Richmond, California]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/42204490/tom-fogerty-invites-you-to-dance/|title=Tom Fogerty Invites You to Dance|date=1976-10-23|work=The Berkeley Gazette|access-date=2020-04-14|pages=20}}</ref> Oda married Jean Nugent in 1985.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ancestry.com/cs/offers/join?sub=2550866976735232&dbid=1144&url=https%3a%2f%2fsearch.ancestry.com%2fcgi-bin%2fsse.dll%3fdbid%3d1144%26h%3d1645299%26indiv%3dtry%26o_vc%3dRecord%3aOtherRecord%26rhSource%3d5247%26requr%3d2550866976735232%26ur%3d0&gsfn=&gsln=&h=1645299|title=California Marriage Index|website=www.ancestry.com|url-access=subscription|url-status=live|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nBeginning in late 1971, Randy Oda, his brother Kevin Oda, Art Pantoja, and Kyle Schneider formed the band \"Oda\", which producing two albums on the Loud Phonograph Albums label.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/42203935/oda_likes_its_records_loud/|title=Oda  Likes Its Records Loud|date=1973-03-17|access-date=2020-01-13|pages=24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/artist/2069706-Oda-4|title=Oda (4)|website=Discogs|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> A local [[San Francisco Bay Area|Bay Area]] band, they played gigs in Berkely.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/42204665/keystone_date/|title=Keystone Date|date=1980-08-29|access-date=2020-01-13|pages=19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/42203521/oda_joy_of_it/|title=Oda Joy of It|date=1983-01-14|work=The Berkeley Gazette|access-date=2020-01-13|pages=19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/43651601/rocker_randy_oda_plays_at_keystone/|title=Rocker Randy Oda plays at Keystone Wednesday|date=1981-12-25|work=The Berkeley Gazette|access-date=2020-02-05|pages=48}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/43651584/oda_headlines_keystone_friday/|title=Oda headlines Keystone Friday|date=1983-02-03|work=The Berkeley Gazette|access-date=2020-02-05|pages=14}}</ref> They played a reunion benefit at [[Concord, California|Concord]] in 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eastbaytimes.com/2015/01/21/chris-treadway-world-series-trophies-playland-reading-benefit-and-garage-band-reunion/|title=Chris Treadway: World Series trophies, Playland reading benefit and garage band reunion|date=2015-01-21|website=East Bay Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-12}}</ref>\n\nIn the early 1970's, Oda joined Tom Fogerty in the band Ruby, with Oda on guitar, Anthony Davis on bass, and [[Bobby Cochran]] on drums. Reviewer Phillip Elwood wrote, \"...when Randy Oda, nominally the band's solo guitar, gets into an extended theme the band backs him with all the flair of a seasoned jazz-blues-rock orchestra.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/42204168/ruby_is_a_futuristic_gem_of_electric/|title=Ruby Is a Futuristic Gem of Electric Rock|date=1976-01-09|work=The San Francisco Examiner|access-date=2020-01-13|pages=25}}</ref>\n\nIn a 1978 review of Ruby, Greg Beese said Oda was \"a session musician prior to joining Ruby, playing on television and radio commercials, including those for [[McDonald's|McDonalds]] restaurants. His sounds transcends the [[Big Mac]], though, as he is a sensitive and hot guitarist. His instrumental composition \"BART\" (after [[Bay Area Rapid Transit]]) immediately picked up the show and shook up the crowd Friday night. Oda's instrumental compositions are not unlike [[Jeff Beck]] or [[Pablo Cruise]] in the way they build up to a whining crescendo.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/42202906/ruby_pleasant_surprise_for_civic/|title=Ruby Pleasant Surprise for Civic|date=1978-04-02|work=Santa Cruz Sentinel|access-date=2020-01-13|pages=17}}</ref> Oda's \"BART\" instrumental was used by the [[BBC]] in school intervals during the 1970s and 1980s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://viralhub.video/video/vfC8M-mTBMM/bbc-schools-music-bart-by-ruby-on-pages-from-ceefax-18th-november-2005|title=BBC Schools Music Bart By Ruby On Pages From Ceefax 18th November 2005|website=viralhub.video|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\nRuby released two studio albums, ''[[Ruby (Ruby album)|Ruby]]'' in 1976<ref>{{Citation|title=Ruby - Ruby {{!}} Songs, Reviews, Credits {{!}} AllMusic|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/ruby-mw0000846581|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> and ''[[Rock & Roll Madness]]'' in 1978,<ref>{{Citation|title=Rock'n'Roll Madness - Ruby {{!}} Songs, Reviews, Credits {{!}} AllMusic|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/rocknroll-madness-mw0000848018|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> and then disbanded. They relased ''[[Precious Gems]]'', a compliation album, in 1984. Oda and Fogerty's ''[[Sidekicks (album)|Sidekicks]] was'' released in 1992 after Fogerty died,<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/43648477/rockin_island_style/|title=Rockin' island style|date=2015-06-18|work=Rapid City Journal|access-date=2020-02-05|pages=32}}</ref> with Oda's credits on the album listed as \"Arranger, Composer, Guitar (Acoustic), Guitar (Electric), Keyboards, Primary Artist, Producer\".<ref>{{Citation|title=Sidekicks - Tom Fogerty {{!}} Credits {{!}} AllMusic|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/sidekicks-mw0000094869/credits|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> \n\nOda composed Eddie Money's 1982 single, \"[[Think I'm in Love (Eddie Money song)|Think I'm in Love]]\", which reached #1 on the ''Billboard'' [[Hot Mainstream Rock Tracks|Top Tracks]] chart.<ref>[[Joel Whitburn|Whitburn, Joel]] (2004). ''The Billboard Book of Top 40 Hits'', 8th Edition (Billboard Publications), page 433.</ref> It appeared on Money's 1983 album, ''[[No Control (Eddie Money album)|No Control]]'',<ref>{{Citation|title=No Control - Eddie Money {{!}} Songs, Reviews, Credits {{!}} AllMusic|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/no-control-mw0000191044|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> as well as [[Arnold Schwarzenegger's Total Body Workout|''Arnold Schwarzenegger's Total Body Workout'']] video,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/arnold-schwarzeneggers-total-body-workout-mw0000324378|title=Arnold Schwarzenegger's Total Body Workout - Arnold Schwarzenegger {{!}} Songs, Reviews, Credits|website=AllMusic|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> and multiple compilation albums.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/randy-oda-mn0000397161/credits|title=Randy Oda {{!}} Credits|website=AllMusic|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\nOda joined his brother Kevin Oda on drums and Michael Politeau (bass) in the band 'OPO, an acronym for its members (Oda, Politeau, Oda), which also means \"to lay a foundation\" in Hawaiian.<ref name=\":0\" /> 'OPO produced the album ''Getaway'' in 2011.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/getaway-mw0002200311|title=Getaway - 'Opo {{!}} Songs, Reviews, Credits|website=AllMusic|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/getaway-mw0002200311/releases|title=Getaway - 'Opo Releases|website=AllMusic|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [http://oposongs.com/bio.html 'OPO band website]\n*{{YouTube|id=59pbyJ4dVrU|title=Think I'm in Love}} (video, 2:37 minute)\n* {{YouTube|title=Oda - I Got a Mind to Give Up Living|id=wiQjBcViiYI}} (audio, 6:25 minutes)\n* {{YouTube|id=vfC8M-mTBMM|title=BART on BBC}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Oda, Randy}}\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American guitarists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American musicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American guitarists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American musicians]]\n[[Category:American male guitarists]]\n[[Category:American rock guitarists]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from California]]\n[[Category:People from Contra Costa County, California]]\n[[Category:Rhythm guitarists]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "relased > released", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Randy_Oda"}
{"title_page": "MasterChef Australia", "text_new": "{{For|the current season|MasterChef Australia (series 12)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=May 2011}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = MasterChef Australia\n| image                = MasterChef Australia Logo & Wordmark.svg\n| director             = Richard Franc\n| creator              = \n| writer               = Esi Bartels\n| presenter            = [[Sarah Wilson (journalist)|Sarah Wilson]] (2009)\n| judges               = {{Plainlist|\n*[[Andy Allen (chef)|Andy Allen]] (2020\u2013)\n*Melissa Leong (2020\u2013)\n*[[Jock Zonfrillo]] (2020\u2013)\n*[[Gary Mehigan]] (2009\u201319)\n*[[George Calombaris]] (2009\u201319)\n*[[Matt Preston]] (2009\u201319)\n}}\n| narrated             = {{Plainlist|\n*[[Nicholas McKay (actor)|Nicholas McKay]] (2009\u201312)\n*Graeme Stone (2013)\n*Lofty Fulton (2014\u2013)\n}}\n| theme_music_composer = {{Plainlist|\n*[[Katy Perry]]\n*[[Dr. Luke|Lukasz Gottwald]]\n*[[Max Martin]]\n}}\n| opentheme            = ''[[Hot n Cold]]''\n| endtheme             = \n| composer             = {{Plainlist|\n*[[Dinesh Wicks]]\n*Adam Gock\n*Anthony Ammar\n}}\n| country              = Australia\n| language             = English\n| num_series           = 12\n| num_episodes         = 753 <!-- as of 20 April 2020 --><!-- Do not uncomment the preceding text. This field is for a number only and the date should not be visible. -->\n| executive_producer   = {{Plainlist|\n*Marty Benson\n*Adam Fergusson\n*Tim Toni\n}}\n| producer             = {{Plainlist|\n*Tim Toni\n}}\n| company              = [[FremantleMedia Australia]] (2009\u201311)<br />[[Endemol Shine Australia]] (2012\u2013)\n| location             = [[Sydney]], [[New South Wales]] (2009\u201312)<br />[[Melbourne]], [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]] (2013\u2013present)\n| runtime              = 30\u2013120&nbsp;minutes per episode\n| channel              = [[Network 10]]\n| picture_format       = [[576i]] ([[SDTV]])<br />[[1080i]] ([[high-definition television|HDTV]]) (2016\u2013 )\n| audio_format         = [[Stereo]]<br />[[Dolby Digital]] [[5.1]]\n| first_run            = \n| first_aired          = 27 April 2009\n| last_aired           = present\n| related              = ''[[Celebrity MasterChef Australia]]'' <br /> ''[[Junior MasterChef Australia]]'' <br /> ''[[MasterChef Australia All-Stars]]'' <br /> ''[[MasterChef Australia: The Professionals]]''\n| preceded_by          = \n| followed_by          = \n| website              = http://www.masterchef.com.au/\n| production_website   = https://www.endemolshine.com.au/#/masterchef/\n}}\n\n'''''MasterChef Australia''''' is an Australian competitive cooking [[game show]] based on the original British ''[[MasterChef (UK TV series)|MasterChef]]''. It is produced by [[Shine Australia]] and screens on [[Network 10]]. Restaurateur and chef [[Gary Mehigan]], chef [[George Calombaris]] and food critic [[Matt Preston]] served as the show's main judges until 2019, when they were replaced by [[MasterChef Australia (series 4)|Series 4]] winner and chef [[Andy Allen (chef)|Andy Allen]], food critic Melissa Leong, and restaurateur and chef [[Jock Zonfrillo]].\n\nThe series has also spawned four spin-off series: ''[[Celebrity MasterChef Australia]]'', which featured celebrity contestants,<ref name=\"celeb\">{{cite web|url=http://www.news.com.au/heraldsun/story/0,21985,25791148-661,00.html|title=Herald Sun|work=news.com.au|accessdate=25 April 2017}}</ref> ''[[Junior MasterChef Australia]]'', which featured younger contestants,<ref name=\"jmc\">{{cite web|url=http://www.news.com.au/couriermail/story/0,23739,26269545-5003422,00.html|title=The Courier Mail|work=news.com.au|accessdate=25 April 2017}}</ref> ''[[MasterChef Australia All-Stars]]'', which featured returning contestants from the first three series,<ref name=\"allstars\" /> and ''[[MasterChef Australia: The Professionals]]'', which featured professional chefs as contestants.<ref name=\"prof\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2012/10/masterchef-the-professionals-vs-my-kitchen-rules.html|title=MasterChef: The Professionals vs My Kitchen Rules?|date=29 October 2012|work=tvtonight.com.au|accessdate=25 April 2017}}</ref> These spin-off shows did not air in 2014 after the producers of the show announced that they wanted to solely focus on the original version.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2013/09/masterchef-sticks-to-one-series-for-2014.html|title=MasterChef sticks to one series for 2014|date=31 August 2013|work=tvtonight.com.au|accessdate=25 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Format==\n''MasterChef Australia'' has a different format from that of the original British ''[[MasterChef (UK TV series)|MasterChef]]'' and ''MasterChef Goes Large'' formats. Initial rounds consist of a large number of hopeful contestants from across Australia individually \"auditioning\" by presenting a food dish before the three judges in order to gain one of 50 semi-final places. Entrants must be over 18 years old and their main source of income cannot come from preparing and cooking fresh food in a professional environment.<ref>{{cite web|first=David|last=Knox|title=Auditions: Masterchef|url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2008/12/auditions-masterchef.html|publisher=tvtonight.com.au|date=9 December 2008|accessdate=12 January 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe semi-finalists then compete in several challenges that test their food knowledge and preparation skills. In Season 1, the top 50 competed until 20 were left, with the final 20 progressing to the main stage of the show. From Season 2, 24 contestants progress. The contestants will then be whittled down through a number of individual and team-based cooking challenges and weekly elimination rounds until a winning MasterChef is crowned. The winner plays for a prize that includes chef training from leading professional chefs, the chance to have their own [[cookbook]] published, and [[A$]]250,000 in cash.\n\n===Episodes===\n''MasterChef Australia'' airs five nights a week from Sunday to Thursday. Each night features a different episode format, however some episodes modify the format slightly. The typical episode formats are as follows:\n\n'''Sunday''' is the ''Challenge'' night. From series 3, it can range from a variety of challenges, including a Mystery Box, where each contestant is given the same box of ingredients and are to create a dish using only those ingredients. The Judges then pick 3 dishes Based on Technique and Visual Appearance Alone and a winner chosen. There can also be an Invention Test, where contestants have to invent a dish relevant to a theme using a core ingredient. There can also be Off-Site Challenges and Team Challenges, which often involve cooking for large numbers of people. The top three contestants who made the best dishes are selected by the judges, from which a winner is chosen to compete in the Immunity Challenge. After this the bottom three are revealed, who will face off in an elimination challenge the next night. In the first two series, it would always consist of a Mystery Box, where the winner was able to choose the core ingredient for the Invention Test.\n\n'''Monday''' episodes feature the ''Pressure Test''. The bottom three from the previous night's challenge are given a recipe for a particular dish they are to emulate in an allocated time. Once completed they are taken in to the judges to be tasted, before all three contestants are seated in front of the judges for critiquing. The judges then eliminate the contestant out of the three that performed least adequately in the test.\n\n'''Tuesday''' episodes feature the ''Immunity Challenge'', where the winner of the Sunday challenge competes against a guest, which can vary from a chef, apprentice, or to a home cook in a cook off. The contestant is given the choice of two pantries of ingredients they can use, usually contrasting such as \"Black\" and \"White\". The contestant gets a head start to complete the dish before their opponent starts cooking and after the allotted time for both is finished, the dishes are presented to the judges for tasting and scoring out of ten. The judges are not aware which dish was made by which person, however. If the contestant's dish's score is equal to or higher than that of the guest, they are crowned the winner of the challenge. In the first series they are given a free pass to the finals week of the competition and can go home. From series 2 onwards, they receive a pin that allows them to save themselves from one future elimination.\n\n'''Wednesday''' features a ''Team Challenge''. The contestants are split into teams, and are given a task, and a set amount of time to complete the challenge. Tasks have included presenting a three course meal to a celebrity guest, running a restaurant for an evening or catering an event such as a birthday party or wedding. Once completed and judged the teams are given the results, which can be determined by which team the judges think did the best, or receiving the most votes or making the most money by the people the teams had to cook for, with members of the losing team facing an elimination the next night. The winning team safe from elimination receives a reward (for example lunch at a top restaurant).\n\n'''Thursday''' is another ''Elimination''. The two worst performing contestants from the losing team in the team challenge compete against each other in a head to head challenge to determine who will be eliminated. The loser of the challenge is then eliminated. On some occasions, all members of the losing team will be selected to compete as individuals in the elimination challenge. In the first series, a different elimination process was used. The contestants from the losing team were to vote for a contestant that they each feel did not perform to their best and may have cost them the challenge. After voting the team is called in together to announce the results of the vote, with the contestant with the most votes being eliminated from the competition. If the previous challenge was an individual challenge, the bottom two contestants competed in a head to head taste test where one contestant at a time named one ingredient of a particular dish or sauce, and the first person to name an incorrect ingredient is eliminated. ''MasterClass'' airs on Thursday following the elimination show and is generally limited to themed weeks. Here, judges George, Gary and Matt run a masterclass for the remaining contestants, which usually call back to some of the challenges from the previous week. For example, they may revisit the Mystery Box challenge and demonstrate some other dishes that could have been made or redo one of the contestants' dishes to give tips on how it could have been improved.\n\n==Hosts and judges==\n===Main series===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"\n|+ Timeline of hosts, judges and other personnel\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:8em;\" rowspan=\"2\"| Starring\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"12\"| Seasons\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3.5em;\"| [[MasterChef Australia (series 1)|1]]\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3.5em;\"| [[MasterChef Australia (series 2)|2]]\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3.5em;\"| [[MasterChef Australia (series 3)|3]]\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3.5em;\"| [[MasterChef Australia (series 4)|4]]\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3.5em;\"| [[MasterChef Australia (series 5)|5]]\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3.5em;\"| [[MasterChef Australia (series 6)|6]]\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3.5em;\"| [[MasterChef Australia (series 7)|7]]\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3.5em;\"| [[MasterChef Australia (series 8)|8]]\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3.5em;\"| [[MasterChef Australia (series 9)|9]]\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3.5em;\"| [[MasterChef Australia (series 10)|10]]\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3.5em;\"| [[MasterChef Australia (series 11)|11]]\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3.5em;\"| [[Mast