ackground:#F0F8FF\"| '''#3'''\n| 0.980\n| style=\"background:#F0F8FF\"| '''#11'''\n| 1.022\n| style=\"background:#F0F8FF\"| '''#9'''\n! style=\"background:#FFFDD0\"| 0.886\n|-\n|- style=\"border-top:3px solid gray; font-weight:bold;\"\n! colspan=\"3\"| Overall average\n| 91\n| 1.423\n| style=\"background:#F0F8FF\"| #2\n| 1.109\n| style=\"background:#F0F8FF\"| #7\n| 1.209\n| style=\"background:#F0F8FF\"| #7\n| style=\"background:#FFFDD0\"| 1.007\n|}\n\n===Critical and popular reception===\nDespite success in ratings, the series initially received mixed reviews, with fans of the original British version describing the Australian show to be incomparable to that version in terms of quality, structure, judgement and skill of the contestant.<ref>{{cite news|title=First taste of Masterchef draws mixed reaction|url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/entertainment/tv--radio/first-taste-of-masterchef-draws-mixed-reaction/2009/04/28/1240684450460.html|work=The Age |date=28 April 2009|accessdate=8 May 2009 | location=Melbourne, Australia}}</ref> Other commentators have also criticised the show for using a competition format similar to other reality shows such as ''[[Australian Idol]]'', ''[[The Biggest Loser]]'' and ''[[Project Runway Australia]]'' that focuses more on the elimination of contestants than the food and cooking itself.<ref>{{cite web|title=If you can't stand the heat...|url=http://www.theblurb.com.au/Issue101/Masterchef.htm|publisher=The Blurb|accessdate=18 May 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090602093301/http://www.theblurb.com.au/Issue101/Masterchef.htm|archive-date=2 June 2009|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Australian Masterchef \u2013 So You Think You Can Cook?|url=http://macabremelbourne.com/blog/2009/04/29/tv-review-australian-masterchef-so-you-think-you-can-cook/|publisher=Macabre Melbourne|date=29 April 2009|accessdate=18 May 2009}} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> Ten's programming chief David Mott admitted that using the new format was \"a huge risk\",<ref name=herald/> while FremantleMedia's Paul Franklin has asserted that \"for a commercial audience we needed to pump it up and make it bigger, a little over the top, with more drama and storytelling and a sense of theatre\".<ref name=TVTwrap/> Since Series 5 (2012) however, when the show began filming in Melbourne, rather than Sydney, the producers changed the original format during the qualifying round for the top 24 to one similar to MasterChef USA; the remainder of the show however stuck more or less to the original Australian format though.\n\nDespite these harsh views, it is still popular amongst many others who have praised the balance of entertainment, skill and overall presentation which is more fun-loving in its (Australian) attitude in comparison with the original British format. The show has been described as \"an antidote for cynicism\" and a reflection of multicultural Australia,<ref name=friends>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/news/masterchefs-appeal-was-its-friends/story-e6frezz0-1225752377676|title=MasterChef's appeal was its friends|work=dailytelegraph.com.au|accessdate=25 April 2017}}</ref> while the show's success has been attributed to audiences \"uncomfortable with the win-at-all-cost mould of reality shows of old\" and a shift in values in the face of the [[Financial crisis of 2007\u20132010|recent financial crisis]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/news/channel-ten-show-masterchef-secret-recipe/story-e6freuy9-1225748411764|title=Channel Ten show MasterChef secret recipe|work=dailytelegraph.com.au|accessdate=25 April 2017}}</ref> As is noted in Australian MasterChef's premier episode of Season 4, since Australian MasterChef premiered in 2009 (the first MasterChef series outside of the UK (est. 1990), it has been such a success that France, Greece, Turkey, Portugal, New Zealand, India, Peru, Finland, Sweden, Italy, Germany, Denmark, Norway, the US and many other countries have all followed Australia's lead and formed their own series of the show in their respective countries; this in itself reveals the popularity of the Australian show from an international audience's perspective compared to that of the British version.\n\n[[Cooking school]]s have reported an increase in enrolments due to the success of the series,<ref>{{cite news|title=Cooking schools flooded with MasterChef fans |url=http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/story/0,28383,25642967-10229,00.html |publisher=news.com.au |date=17 June 2009|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090618104441/http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/story/0%2C28383%2C25642967-10229%2C00.html |archivedate=18 June 2009 }}</ref> while kitchenware retailers and upmarket restaurants have also seen increased trade. Supermarkets and specialty food retailers have reported increased demand from the public for more unusual ingredients, such as quail, custard apple and squab, after such were featured on the program.<ref>{{cite news|title=MasterChef fans drive specialty boom|url=https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/tv-and-radio/masterchef-fans-drive-specialty-boom-20100726-10smk.html|publisher=Sydney Morning Herald|date=27 July 2010|accessdate=27 July 2010 | first1=Rachel | last1=Olding | first2=Jacqui | last2=Taffel}}</ref> The success of the show led Ten to explore possible spin-offs such as the celebrity and junior versions, as well as one featuring professional chefs as contestants.<ref name=celeb/> The success of the show has also led competing networks to commission their own competitive cooking programs, such as Seven's ''[[My Kitchen Rules]]'' and Nine's ''The Great Aussie Cook-Off'' after the first series of the Australian version,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/news/entertainment/tv--radio/masterchef-inspires-imitators/2009/08/05/1249350576139.html|title=MasterChef inspires imitators \u2013 TV & Radio \u2013 Entertainment \u2013 smh.com.au|work=smh.com.au|accessdate=25 April 2017}}</ref> with reports that both networks were planning more copycat shows to air in late 2010 and early 2011.\n\n''MasterChef Australia'' won the award for Most Popular Reality Program at the [[Logie Awards of 2010|2010 Logie Awards]]. In addition, Matt Preston won the Graham Kennedy Award for Most Outstanding New Talent for his work on the program.<ref name=\"logies2010\">{{Cite news\n  | title = 2010 Logie Awards: round-up\n  | work=The Spy Report\n  | publisher=Media Spy\n  | date = 3 May 2010\n  | url = http://www.mediaspy.org/report/2010/05/03/2010-logie-awards-round-up/\n  | accessdate =18 May 2010\n}}</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\n===Allegations of vote rigging===\nSignificant numbers of viewers have raised allegations that the voting on the series one finale of ''MasterChef'' was fraudulent after Julie Goodwin won the crown. After the airing of the finale [[talkback radio]] became inundated with calls, both for and against the verdict, and the finale also became a top trending topic on social networking site Twitter, where many users said they felt \"deflated\" and \"ripped off\" by the final episode of the hit show.<ref name=newsrigged>{{cite news|title=Was MasterChef Australia rigged? |url=http://www.news.com.au/perthnow/story/0,21598,25807502-5005382,00.html |date=20 July 2009 |accessdate=20 July 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090724175641/http://www.news.com.au/perthnow/story/0%2C21598%2C25807502-5005382%2C00.html |archivedate=24 July 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Julie Beats Poh \u2013 Masterchef Australia Rigged?|url=http://www.youngandgrumpy.com/2009/07/julie-beats-poh-masterchef-australia.html|date=20 July 2009|accessdate=20 July 2009}}</ref> Similar allegations were raised when contestants were eliminated throughout the series.<ref name=preston>{{cite news|title=MasterChef judge Matt Preston denies show is rigged|url=http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/story/0,28383,25670473-10388,00.html|date=22 June 2009|accessdate=20 July 2009 | work=news.com.au}}</ref>\n\nJudge Matt Preston has denied that eliminations were rigged or the result of a popularity contest,<ref name=preston/> and asserted that Julie had won the title because she was the better cook on the night.<ref name=newsrigged/> Goodwin herself has also asserted that her victory was not the result of rigging, insisting that the professional integrity of the three judges would be damaged if it were.<ref>{{cite news|title=MasterChef's Julie Goodwin says show wasn't rigged|url=http://www.news.com.au/heraldsun/story/0,21985,25808205-5005961,00.html|date=20 July 2009|accessdate=20 July 2009 | first=Katherine | last=Field}}</ref>\n\n===Welfare of former contestants===\nDuring their time playing ''MasterChef'', the contestants are paid a retainer of $500 a week. This is slightly below the national Australian minimum wage of $589.30 and less than half the average wage of $1,291.34. However, contestants have their accommodation provided for the duration of their time in the competition, meaning they live rent-free. These facts were revealed in 2011 along with the knowledge that most contestants quit their jobs before entering the competition and faced seeking re-employment once eliminated from the show.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/television/revealed-the-masterchef-weekly-wage/story-fn8gfhpl-1226097021400 | work=news.com.au | first=Alison | last=Stephenson | title=Revealed: The MasterChef weekly wage | date=19 July 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Marco Pierre White===\nFollowing comments made by judge Matt Preston about [[Marco Pierre White|Marco's]] son's admitted $500,000 splurge of his father's money on drugs and prostitution,<ref name=\"Gray\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nowtolove.com.au/news/latest-news/marco-pierre-white-jr-foul-tirade-matt-preston-37304|title=Marco Pierre White Jr's foul-mouthed tirade against Matt Preston will shock you (to say the least!)|first=Lorna|last=Gray|work=www.nowtolove.com.au|date=9 May 2017|accessdate=14 May 2017}}</ref> Marco joined the rival programme [[Hell's Kitchen Australia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kiis1011.com.au/entertainment/celebrity-gossip/marco-pierre-white-has-revealed-the-real-reason-as-to-why-he-quit-masterchef|title=MARCO PIERRE WHITE REVEALS REASON WHY HE QUIT MASTERCHEF|work=kiis1011.com.au|date=8 May 2017|accessdate=14 May 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170508021247/http://www.kiis1011.com.au/entertainment/celebrity-gossip/marco-pierre-white-has-revealed-the-real-reason-as-to-why-he-quit-masterchef|archive-date=8 May 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> In 2016, whilst on [[The Kyle and Jackie O Show]] Preston was asked about Marco Jr.\u2019s time on [[Big Brother (UK TV series)|Big Brother UK]], which included his alleged on\u2013air sex and the above admission to purchasing illicit drugs and sex workers. Preston said \"I think it is that terrible thing when you have kids that go off the rails... the drugs might be a little bit of a worry\". This sparked a series of profanity\u2013filled social media attacks by Marco Jr. which he has since apologised for on the Kyle and Jackie O Show.<ref name=\"Gray\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/tv/radio/marco-pierre-white-jr-addresses-matt-preston-feud-it-was-disgraceful/news-story/284fd031d8e4a82e247f5bd1ad293fd1|title=Marco Pierre White Jr addresses Matt Preston feud: 'It was disgraceful'|work=news.com.au|date=9 May 2017|accessdate=14 May 2017}}</ref> Since quitting Masterchef, Marco Snr has said that \u201cI will never forgive that man...with my hand on my mother\u2019s grave I will get that man\u201d and joined Hell's Kitchen Australia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/tv/reality-tv/celeb-chef-marco-pierre-whites-angry-feud-with-matt-preston-i-will-never-forgive-him/news-story/872a213c6f703c1570e6b59a64e0ebb2|title=Celeb chef Marco Pierre White's angry feud with Matt Preston: 'I will never forgive him'|work=news.com.au|date=8 May 2017|accessdate=14 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n==International syndication==\n{{unreferenced section|date=June 2019}}\nThe network in '''bold''' also broadcast their own version of ''MasterChef''.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Country || Network || Dubbed or subtitled? || Current broadcaster?\n|-\n| Afghanistan || [[STAR World]] || Subtitled in Dari || rowspan=5|No\n|-\n|rowspan=2|Arab League || [[Fox Series]] || Dubbed\n|-\n|[[STAR World]]\n|-\n| Bangladesh || [[STAR World India]] || Subtitled in English\n|-\n|rowspan=2|Belgium || [[\u00e9\u00e9n]] ||rowspan=2| Subtitled in Dutch\n|-\n|[[Vitaya]] || rowspan=1|Yes\n|-\n| Bhutan || [[STAR World India]] || Subtitled in English || rowspan=3|No\n|-\n| Brazil || [[Travel & Living Channel]] || Dubbed\n|-\n| Burma || [[STAR World]] || Subtitled\n|-\n|rowspan=2|Canada || [[Casa (TV channel)|Casa]] || Dubbed in French || rowspan=2|Yes\n|-\n| [[CTV Life Channel|CTV Life (formerly Gusto)]] ||\n|-\n| Croatia || '''[[Nova TV (Croatia)|Nova TV]]''' ||rowspan=5| Subtitled || rowspan=6|No\n|-\n| Denmark || [[TV3 Puls]]\n|-\n|rowspan=2|Finland || [[Jim (TV channel)|Jim]]\n|-\n| '''[[Nelonen]]'''\n|-\n| Greece || '''[[Mega Channel]]'''\n|-\n| Hong Kong || [[Lifetime (TV network)|Lifetime]] || Subtitled in Chinese\n|-\n| India || '''[[STAR World India]]'''<br />[[Living Foodz]]<br />[[Zee Cafe]]|| Subtitled in English || Yes\n|-\n|rowspan=2|Indonesia || [[TVN (Indonesia)|B-Channel]] (now [[Rajawali Televisi|RTV]]) || rowspan=2|Subtitled || rowspan=8|No\n|-\n| [[Lifetime (TV network)|Lifetime]]\n|-\n|rowspan=4|Ireland || [[Good Food]]\n|-\n| [[Really (TV channel)|Really]]\n|-\n| '''[[RT\u00c9 One]]'''\n|-\n| [[Watch (TV channel)|Watch]]\n|-\n| Israel || [[Channel 2 (Israel)|Channel 2]] || Subtitled in Hebrew \n|-\n| rowspan=3|Italy || [[Gambero Rosso]] || Dubbed\n|-\n| [[cielo (TV channel)]] || Dubbed || rowspan=1| Yes\n|-\n| [[Sky Uno]] || Dubbed || rowspan=1| Yes\n|-\n| Macau || rowspan=\"2\" | [